<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch-components" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Components</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      This chapter demonstrates the syntax of common components of a book
      written in <c>bookdown</c>, including code chunks, figures, tables,
      citations, math theorems, and equations. The approach is based on
      Pandoc, so we start with the syntax of Pandoc's flavor of Markdown.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="markdown-syntax">
    <title>Markdown syntax</title>

    <p>
      In this section, we give a very brief introduction to Pandoc's Markdown.
      Readers who are familiar with Markdown can skip this section. The
      comprehensive syntax of Pandoc's Markdown can be found on the Pandoc
      website <url href="http://pandoc.org" visual="pandoc.org"/>.
    </p>

    <subsection xml:id="inline-formatting">
      <title>Inline formatting</title>

      <p>
        You can make text <em>italic</em> by surrounding it with underscores or
        asterisks, for example, <c>_text_</c> or <c>*text*</c>. For
        <em>bold</em> text, use two underscores (<c>__text__</c>) or asterisks
        (<c>**text**</c>). Text surrounded by <c>~</c> will be converted to a
        subscript, and similarly, two carets (<c>^</c>) produce a superscript.
        To mark text as <c>inline code</c>, use a pair of backticks, for
        example, <c>`code`</c>. Small caps can be produced by the HTML tag
        <c>span</c>, links are created using <c>[text](link)</c>, and the
        syntax for images is similar: just add an exclamation mark. Footnotes
        are put inside the square brackets after a caret, for example,
        <c>^[This is a footnote.]</c>. We will talk about citations later in
        this chapter.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="block-level-elements">
      <title>Block-level elements</title>

      <p>Section headers can be written after a number of pound signs, for example,</p>

      <program language="markdown">
        <input># First-level header

## Second-level header

### Third-level header</input>
      </program>

      <p>
        If you do not want a certain heading to be numbered, you can add
        <c>{-}</c> after the heading.
      </p>

      <program language="markdown">
        <input># Preface {-}</input>
      </program>

      <p>
        Unordered list items start with <c>*</c>, <c>-</c>, or <c>+</c>, and
        you can nest one list within another list by indenting the sub-list by
        four spaces.
      </p>

      <program language="markdown">
        <input>- one item
- one item
- one item
    - one item
    - one item</input>
      </program>

      <p>The output is:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><p>one item</p></li>
        <li><p>one item</p></li>
        <li>
          <p>one item</p>
          <ul>
            <li><p>one item</p></li>
            <li><p>one item</p></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Ordered list items start with numbers (the rule for nested lists is the
        same as above).
      </p>

      <program language="markdown">
        <input>1. the first item
2. the second item
3. the third item</input>
      </program>

      <p>The output does not look too much different with the Markdown source:</p>

      <ol>
        <li><p>the first item</p></li>
        <li><p>the second item</p></li>
        <li><p>the third item</p></li>
      </ol>

      <p>Blockquotes are written after <c>&gt;</c>, and the Rmd source uses a Mark Twain quotation as its example.</p>

      <program language="markdown">
        <input>&gt; A blockquote example
&gt;
&gt; --- Mark Twain</input>
      </program>

      <blockquote>
        <p>A blockquote example.</p>
        <p>— Mark Twain</p>
      </blockquote>

      <p>
        Plain code blocks can be written after three or more backticks, and you
        can also indent the blocks by four spaces.
      </p>

      <program language="markdown">
        <input>```
This text is displayed verbatim / preformatted
```

Or indent by four spaces:

    This text is displayed verbatim / preformatted</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="math-expressions">
      <title>Math expressions</title>

      <p>
        Inline LaTeX equations can be written in a pair of dollar signs using
        the LaTeX syntax, for example,
        <c>$f(k) = {n \choose k} p^{k} (1-p)^{n-k}$</c>; math expressions of
        the display style can be written in a pair of double dollar signs.
      </p>

      <md>
        f\left(k\right)=\binom{n}{k}p^k\left(1-p\right)^{n-k}
      </md>

      <p>You can also use math environments inside dollar pairs, for example,</p>

      <program language="latex">
        <input>$$\begin{array}{ccc}
x_{11} &amp; x_{12} &amp; x_{13}\\
x_{21} &amp; x_{22} &amp; x_{23}
\end{array}$$</input>
      </program>

      <program language="latex">
        <input>$$X = \begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; x_{1}\\
1 &amp; x_{2}\\
1 &amp; x_{3}
\end{bmatrix}$$</input>
      </program>

      <program language="latex">
        <input>$$\Theta = \begin{pmatrix}\alpha &amp; \beta\\
\gamma &amp; \delta
\end{pmatrix}$$</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="markdown-extensions">
    <title>Markdown extensions by bookdown</title>

    <p>
      Although Pandoc's Markdown is much richer than the original Markdown
      syntax, it still lacks a number of things that we may need for academic
      writing. For example, it supports math equations, but you cannot number
      and reference equations in multi-page HTML or EPUB output. We have
      provided a few Markdown extensions in <c>bookdown</c> to fill the gaps.
    </p>

    <subsection xml:id="equations">
      <title>Number and reference equations</title>

      <p>
        To number and refer to equations, put them in equation environments and
        assign labels to them using the syntax <c>(#eq:label)</c>.
      </p>

      <program language="latex">
        <input>\begin{equation}
  f\left(k\right) = \binom{n}{k} p^k\left(1-p\right)^{n-k}
  (#eq:binom)
\end{equation}</input>
      </program>

      <p>It renders the equation below:</p>

      <md>
        f\left(k\right)=\binom{n}{k}p^k\left(1-p\right)^{n-k}
      </md>

      <aside>
        <title>Caution</title>
        <p>
          All labels in <c>bookdown</c> must only contain alphanumeric
          characters, <c>:</c>, <c>-</c>, and/or <c>/</c>. Equation references
          work best for LaTeX/PDF output, and they are not well supported in
          Word output or e-books. For HTML output, <c>bookdown</c> can only
          number the equations with labels.
        </p>
      </aside>

      <program language="latex">
        <input>\begin{equation*}
\frac{d}{dx}\left( \int_{a}^{x} f(u)\,du\right)=f(x)
\end{equation*}</input>
      </program>

      <program language="latex">
        <input>\begin{align}
g(X_{n}) &amp;= g(\theta)+g'({\tilde{\theta}})(X_{n}-\theta) \notag \\
\sqrt{n}[g(X_{n})-g(\theta)] &amp;= g'\left({\tilde{\theta}}\right)
  \sqrt{n}[X_{n}-\theta ] (#eq:align)
\end{align}</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="theorems">
      <title>Theorems and proofs</title>

      <p>
        Theorems and proofs are commonly used in articles and books in
        mathematics. However, please do not be misled by the names: a theorem
        is just a numbered or labeled environment, and it does not have to be a
        mathematical theorem. Similarly, a proof is an unnumbered environment.
      </p>

      <program language="markdown">
        <input>::: {.theorem}
This is a `theorem` environment that can contain **any**
_Markdown_ syntax.
:::</input>
      </program>

      <program language="markdown">
        <input>::: {.theorem #pyth name="Pythagorean theorem"}
For a right triangle, if $c$ denotes the length of the hypotenuse
and $a$ and $b$ denote the lengths of the other two sides, we have

$$a^2 + b^2 = c^2$$
:::</input>
      </program>

      <p>
        The original Rmd chapter continues with definition, example, lemma,
        theorem, proposition, proof, remark, corollary, exercise, solution,
        and hypothesis examples to demonstrate the default theorem styles. Its
        inline output also notes that the proof environments currently supported
        are <c>proof</c>, <c>remark</c>, and <c>solution</c>; for LaTeX output,
        the <c>definition</c> theorem style is used for <c>definition</c>,
        <c>example</c>, <c>exercise</c>, and <c>hypothesis</c>, while the
        <c>remark</c> style is used for <c>proof</c> and <c>remark</c>.
      </p>

      <subsubsection xml:id="theorem-engine">
        <title>A note on the old syntax</title>

        <p>
          For older versions of <c>bookdown</c> (before v0.21), a theorem
          environment could be written with an older fenced-code syntax. This
          still works, but the newer fenced-Div syntax is recommended.
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>bookdown::fence_theorems("01-intro.Rmd", output = "01-intro-new.Rmd")</input>
        </program>
      </subsubsection>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="special-headers">
      <title>Special headers</title>

      <p>
        There are a few special types of first-level headers that will be
        processed differently in <c>bookdown</c>, including <c>(PART)</c>
        headers for parts and <c>(APPENDIX)</c> headers for appendices.
      </p>

      <program language="markdown">
        <input># (PART) Part I {-}

# Chapter One

# Chapter Two

# (PART) Part II {-}

# Chapter Three</input>
      </program>

      <program language="markdown">
        <input># Chapter One

# Chapter Two

# (APPENDIX) Appendix {-}

# Appendix A

# Appendix B</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="text-references">
      <title>Text references</title>

      <p>
        You can assign some text to a label and reference the text using the
        label elsewhere in your document. This can be particularly useful for
        long figure and table captions.
      </p>

      <program language="markdown">
        <input>(ref:foo) Define a text reference **here**.</input>
      </program>

      <program language="markdown">
        <input>A normal paragraph.

(ref:foo) A scatterplot of the data `cars` using **base** R graphics.

```{r foo, fig.cap='(ref:foo)'}
plot(cars)  # a scatterplot
```</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="r-code">
    <title>R code</title>

    <p>
      There are two types of R code in R Markdown and <c>knitr</c> documents:
      R code chunks, and inline R code.
    </p>

    <program language="markdown">
      <input>```{r chunk-label, echo = FALSE, fig.cap = 'A figure caption.'}
1 + 1
rnorm(10)  # 10 random numbers
plot(dist ~ speed, cars)  # a scatterplot
```</input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="figures">
    <title>Figures</title>

    <p>
      By default, figures have no captions in the output generated by
      <c>knitr</c>. If we assign a figure caption to a code chunk via the chunk
      option <c>fig.cap</c>, R plots will be put into figure environments,
      automatically labeled and numbered, and can also be cross-referenced.
    </p>

    <aside>
      <title>Important</title>
      <p>
        If you want to cross-reference figures or tables generated from a code
        chunk, please make sure the chunk label only contains alphanumeric
        characters, slashes, or dashes.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <program language="r">
      <input>```{r pressure-plot, fig.asp=.7, fig.width=6, fig.cap='A figure example with the specified aspect ratio, width, and alignment.', fig.align='center', out.width='90%'}
par(mar = c(4, 4, .1, .1))
plot(pressure, pch = 19, type = 'b')
```</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>```{r cars-plot, out.width='70%', fig.cap='A figure example with a relative width 70\%.'}
par(mar = c(4, 4, .1, .1))
plot(cars, pch = 19)
```</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>```{r multi-plots, out.width='50%', fig.show='hold', fig.cap='Two plots placed side by side.'}
par(mar = c(4, 4, .1, .1))
plot(pressure, pch = 19, type = 'b')
plot(cars, pch = 19)
```</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>```{r knitr-logo, out.width='32.8%', fig.show='hold', fig.cap='Three knitr logos included in the document from an external PNG image file.'}
knitr::include_graphics(rep('images/knit-logo.png', 3))
```</input>
    </program>

    <figure xml:id="fig-knitr-logo-pretext">
      <title>Three knitr logos included in the document from an external PNG image file.</title>
      <image source="../assets/images/knit-logo.png" width="35%">
        <description>
          <p>The knitr logo image reused from the Rmd example assets.</p>
        </description>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="tables">
    <title>Tables</title>

    <p>
      For now, the most convenient way to generate a table is the function
      <c>knitr::kable()</c>, because there are some internal tricks in
      <c>knitr</c> to make it work with <c>bookdown</c>.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>```{r table-single, tidy=FALSE}
knitr::kable(
  head(mtcars[, 1:8], 10), booktabs = TRUE,
  caption = 'A table of the first 10 rows of the mtcars data.'
)
```</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>```{r table-multi, tidy=FALSE}
knitr::kable(
  list(
    head(iris[, 1:2], 3),
    head(mtcars[, 1:3], 5)
  ),
  caption = 'A Tale of Two Tables.', booktabs = TRUE
)
```</input>
    </program>

    <program language="markdown">
      <input>Table: A simple table in Markdown.

 Sepal.Length   Sepal.Width   Petal.Length   Petal.Width
-------------  ------------  -------------  ------------
          5.1           3.5            1.4           0.2
          4.9           3.0            1.4           0.2
          4.7           3.2            1.3           0.2</input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="cross-references">
    <title>Cross-references</title>

    <p>
      You can reference sections using the same syntax <c>\@ref(label)</c>,
      where <c>label</c> is the section ID. By default, Pandoc will generate an
      ID for all section headers, but it is safer to assign IDs manually.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="custom-blocks">
    <title>Custom blocks</title>

    <p>
      Custom blocks are often used in technical books to create salient boxes
      of code and/or narrative that call the reader's attention, such as notes
      and warnings.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="citations">
    <title>Citations</title>

    <p>
      Pandoc offers two methods for managing citations and bibliographic
      references in a document: <c>pandoc-citeproc</c>, or a PDF-only citation
      package such as <c>natbib</c> or <c>biblatex</c>.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>output:
  pdf_document:
    citation_package: natbib
  bookdown::pdf_book:
    citation_package: biblatex</input>
    </program>

    <program language="bibtex">
      <input>@Manual{R-base,
  title = {R: A Language and Environment for Statistical
    Computing},
  author = {{R Core Team}},
  organization = {R Foundation for Statistical Computing},
  address = {Vienna, Austria},
  year = {2016},
  url = {https://www.R-project.org/},
}</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>```{r write-bib, comment='', warning=FALSE}
# the second argument can be a .bib file
knitr::write_bib(c('knitr', 'stringr'), '', width = 60)
```</input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="latex-index">
    <title>Index</title>

    <p>
      Currently the index is only supported for LaTeX/PDF output. To print an
      index after the book, you can use the LaTeX package <c>makeidx</c> in
      the preamble.
    </p>

    <program language="latex">
      <input>\usepackage{makeidx}
\makeindex</input>
    </program>

    <subsection xml:id="inserting-index-entries">
      <title>Inserting Entries</title>

      <program language="latex">
        <input>Version Control\index{Version Control} is an
important component of the SDLC.</input>
      </program>

      <program language="latex">
        <input>Git\index{Version Control!Git} is a
popular version control system.</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="building-the-index">
      <title>Building the Index</title>

      <p>
        To build the index, insert <c>\printindex</c> at the end of your book
        through the YAML option <c>includes -&gt; after_body</c>.
      </p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="html-widgets">
    <title>HTML widgets</title>

    <p>
      HTML widgets were originally designed for HTML output only, and they
      require the availability of JavaScript, so they will not work in
      non-HTML output formats, such as LaTeX/PDF.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>```{r eval=FALSE}
install.packages('webshot')
webshot::install_phantomjs()
```</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>```{r DT-demo, fig.cap='A table widget rendered via the DT package.', dev='png', cache=TRUE, cache.extra=packageVersion('DT'), screenshot.opts=list(zoom=2), out.width=if(knitr::is_latex_output()) '100%'}
DT::datatable(iris)
```</input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="web-pages-and-shiny-apps">
    <title>Web pages and Shiny apps</title>

    <p>
      Similar to HTML widgets, arbitrary web pages can be embedded in the book
      with <c>knitr::include_url()</c>. The related function
      <c>knitr::include_app()</c> was designed for embedding Shiny apps.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>```{r miniUI, fig.cap='A Shiny app created via the miniUI package; you can see a live version at https://yihui.shinyapps.io/miniUI/.', screenshot.opts=list(delay=20,zoom=2), dev='png', cache=TRUE, fig.align='center', fig.width=8, fig.height=6, out.width=if(knitr::is_latex_output()) '100%'}
knitr::include_app('https://yihui.shinyapps.io/miniUI/', height = '600px')
```</input>
    </program>
  </section>
</chapter>
